WEBVTT

00:00:10.530 --> 00:00:11.400
Good morning, everyone.

00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:11.950
My name is James Craig.

00:00:11.980 --> 00:00:14.020
I'm a member of the
Apple Accessibility team.

00:00:14.170 --> 00:00:16.690
What you're going to see
here is years of work,

00:00:16.700 --> 00:00:18.900
a culmination of years of work
by a lot of different people,

00:00:18.900 --> 00:00:21.460
and so I'm really thrilled that I get
to be the one to share it with you.

00:00:21.710 --> 00:00:26.270
So first off, who here by a show of hands
knows or thinks they know what

00:00:26.270 --> 00:00:28.570
I mean by the term accessibility?

00:00:28.670 --> 00:00:30.300
Okay, good number.

00:00:30.460 --> 00:00:33.000
Some of you are probably
content publishers,

00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:35.750
and you may be aware that
you need to make your content

00:00:35.770 --> 00:00:37.690
compliant or accessible,
and you're not really

00:00:37.710 --> 00:00:38.400
sure what that means.

00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:42.730
And so we're going to cover some of that,
figure out how to test with VoiceOver,

00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:47.070
figure out where your problems
are so you'll know what to fix.

00:00:47.610 --> 00:00:49.250
and some of you are developers.

00:00:49.250 --> 00:00:53.160
This is a developer conference after
all and so you may already be aware of

00:00:53.610 --> 00:00:56.850
accessibility and certain techniques but
you're not really sure which ones are the

00:00:56.850 --> 00:00:58.740
right ones to use in certain situations.

00:00:58.740 --> 00:01:02.180
So we're going to give you a bunch
of examples and talk about how to

00:01:02.230 --> 00:01:05.600
make your book content specifically
as accessible as possible to as

00:01:05.760 --> 00:01:07.460
wide an audience as possible.

00:01:07.530 --> 00:01:11.110
But accessibility isn't really
about code or compliance or

00:01:11.170 --> 00:01:13.530
techniques to use or even testing.

00:01:13.560 --> 00:01:16.550
Accessibility at its core
is really about people.

00:01:16.740 --> 00:01:20.170
And that includes people who may be
using a computing device for the first

00:01:20.170 --> 00:01:25.490
time in their life and even if they
don't consider themselves disabled,

00:01:25.610 --> 00:01:28.170
maybe they don't see as well as
they used to or maybe they don't

00:01:28.170 --> 00:01:29.910
hear as well as they used to.

00:01:30.450 --> 00:01:34.900
It includes people that may be accessing
course content or watching a video,

00:01:34.900 --> 00:01:39.190
even if that means that they need to
watch it with the captions turned on.

00:01:40.920 --> 00:01:43.830
And still,
it means people that just want to

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:48.620
access the same content and have
access to the same tools and read the

00:01:48.620 --> 00:01:51.540
same books that everyone else does,
even if they don't have the same

00:01:51.610 --> 00:01:53.240
abilities that everyone else does.

00:01:53.390 --> 00:01:55.310
And I'm not talking about
small numbers either.

00:01:55.450 --> 00:01:58.820
50 million people in the US alone,
worldwide numbers are

00:01:58.890 --> 00:02:00.830
unknown but obviously larger.

00:02:00.960 --> 00:02:03.640
Some of you may think,
"I don't really relate to that.

00:02:03.660 --> 00:02:05.870
I don't know anybody with a
disability." Chances are you're

00:02:05.870 --> 00:02:07.900
wrong and you just don't realize it.

00:02:07.970 --> 00:02:10.560
Colorblindness, for example,
is one of the more common disabilities.

00:02:10.600 --> 00:02:16.680
It affects, in the male population,
about 8%. That's 1 in 12.

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:19.900
Just looking around the room
and given the stats of the

00:02:19.900 --> 00:02:23.970
Developer Conference this year,
there's probably quite a few people in

00:02:24.010 --> 00:02:26.360
the room here that are affected by this.

00:02:27.830 --> 00:02:31.700
Out of that 50 million,
31 million have a hearing impairment.

00:02:31.700 --> 00:02:35.700
10 million people have
a vision impairment.

00:02:35.700 --> 00:02:37.700
And I'm not talking about
people that wear glasses,

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:40.020
I'm talking about people with
severe non-correctable vision

00:02:40.680 --> 00:02:44.530
impairments like usually people
who are blind or legally blind.

00:02:45.180 --> 00:02:48.840
And so I'm glad I get a chance to
talk to you about iOS today because

00:02:48.990 --> 00:02:54.680
it's had accessibility features built
in since iOS 3 for three years now.

00:02:55.100 --> 00:02:57.700
Captions going farther back than that.

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:00.320
And we've done a lot of hard work.

00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:04.600
We're trying to put in a lot of the work
so that you don't have to do everything.

00:03:04.690 --> 00:03:10.460
And some of the features are a screen
reader for people who are blind,

00:03:10.580 --> 00:03:15.990
Zoom for people with low vision,
captions and LED flash and custom

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:18.940
vibrations for people who maybe
have hearing impairments and

00:03:18.940 --> 00:03:23.530
more features for people with
physical motor impairments and most

00:03:23.530 --> 00:03:26.130
recently with learning impairments.

00:03:28.540 --> 00:03:30.770
and the disability
advocacy groups love us.

00:03:30.830 --> 00:03:36.140
We get quotes like this one from RNIB,
which is a blindness

00:03:36.150 --> 00:03:38.160
advocacy group in the UK.

00:03:38.300 --> 00:03:41.700
When it comes to embedding accessibility,
Apple set a standard in recent years.

00:03:41.810 --> 00:03:42.960
That's pretty amazing.

00:03:42.960 --> 00:03:44.360
We love to hear stuff like that.

00:03:44.450 --> 00:03:46.280
And iBooks is no exception.

00:03:46.280 --> 00:03:51.500
It's had accessibility built in since
the original release with the first iPad.

00:03:52.150 --> 00:03:57.130
and this is a quote from Bradley Hodges
of the American Foundation for the Blind.

00:03:57.130 --> 00:04:00.330
"I believe that accessible iBooks
will be viewed by future generations

00:04:00.330 --> 00:04:03.760
as one of the landmark events
in the lives of the blind." Now,

00:04:03.760 --> 00:04:04.830
how huge is that, right?

00:04:04.890 --> 00:04:06.170
That's a great responsibility.

00:04:06.170 --> 00:04:09.070
It's a great responsibility for us,
but it's also a great responsibility

00:04:09.450 --> 00:04:12.280
for you as the content publishers.

00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:15.550
Now, I said that iBooks has
accessibility built in,

00:04:15.720 --> 00:04:17.700
but there are a few things that
you need to do to make sure

00:04:17.700 --> 00:04:19.720
your content is 100% accessible.

00:04:19.790 --> 00:04:22.480
And that's what we're
going to cover today.

00:04:22.590 --> 00:04:26.780
So, first off, we're going to cover basic
HTML accessibility in EPUB books.

00:04:27.870 --> 00:04:30.880
We're going to cover how to use
VoiceOver to test your books,

00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:35.020
both EPUB and iBooks author books,
so that you can know

00:04:35.030 --> 00:04:36.500
where the problems are.

00:04:37.730 --> 00:04:42.160
I'm going to show you some new features
of iBooks Author for accessibility.

00:04:42.210 --> 00:04:46.420
And we're going to talk about how to
make custom HTML5 widgets so that you can

00:04:46.420 --> 00:04:51.970
embed rich interactive web applications
inside your iBooks Author books.

00:04:53.030 --> 00:04:56.150
So, has anyone here used EPUB before?

00:04:56.430 --> 00:04:58.700
Familiar with EPUB a little bit?

00:04:58.820 --> 00:05:01.810
It's the most common e-book standard.

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:04.230
Novels, for example,
most of the ones that you would

00:05:04.230 --> 00:05:05.900
buy on the iBook store and EPUB.

00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:09.850
And you don't need to know anything
specific about the file format other

00:05:10.110 --> 00:05:11.830
than it's basically a zip folder.

00:05:11.890 --> 00:05:14.170
It has a couple metadata files,
but most of the content

00:05:14.170 --> 00:05:15.900
inside of it is web content.

00:05:16.050 --> 00:05:20.970
So, it's HTML pages,
one or more HTML pages,

00:05:20.970 --> 00:05:26.300
and all the resources
that go along with that.

00:05:26.300 --> 00:05:26.300
So, CSS, JavaScript, and images.

00:05:26.610 --> 00:05:30.570
One of the things I want you to keep in
mind about images is that some images

00:05:30.570 --> 00:05:33.970
look better on certain backgrounds,
dark backgrounds, light backgrounds.

00:05:34.050 --> 00:05:35.940
Some images have transparency.

00:05:36.090 --> 00:05:40.500
And if you're lucky like us,
you'll get a design team that takes

00:05:40.550 --> 00:05:44.670
care to make sure all of the images
that are transparent or should be

00:05:44.670 --> 00:05:49.140
transparent are transparent so they
look great on all different backgrounds,

00:05:49.140 --> 00:05:51.970
whether that be black or white.

00:05:52.300 --> 00:05:54.380
But there's always multiple
versions of the images.

00:05:54.390 --> 00:05:58.590
Or maybe there's a, you know,
someone's made a mistake with an image.

00:05:59.070 --> 00:06:01.490
or maybe it was intended
for another context.

00:06:01.540 --> 00:06:04.820
This one, for example,
looks great on white.

00:06:04.820 --> 00:06:07.790
But because of a transparency error,
because of a transparency issue,

00:06:07.800 --> 00:06:10.900
it wasn't maybe intended
for a black background,

00:06:10.950 --> 00:06:12.550
it doesn't convey the same meaning.

00:06:12.650 --> 00:06:15.780
It may be completely legible
on different backgrounds.

00:06:15.780 --> 00:06:18.260
That's one of the things
I want you to test.

00:06:18.540 --> 00:06:21.190
Let's take a look at an iBook.

00:06:21.290 --> 00:06:23.760
This is our sample iBook.

00:06:23.780 --> 00:06:26.940
It's about astronomy.

00:06:26.940 --> 00:06:26.940
And I

00:06:27.890 --> 00:06:29.340
It has some great images of space here.

00:06:29.340 --> 00:06:33.140
Let's see what they look
like on a dark background.

00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:35.470
I'm going to switch it to night mode.

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:36.890
Sure enough, it looks great.

00:06:36.900 --> 00:06:37.860
These are space images.

00:06:38.030 --> 00:06:39.520
There's no transparency in here.

00:06:39.710 --> 00:06:42.700
In fact, they look even better
on the black background.

00:06:42.700 --> 00:06:45.880
So we don't have trouble here,
but if you're looking at your books,

00:06:45.930 --> 00:06:48.300
double-check them in
all different themes.

00:06:48.450 --> 00:06:51.400
But I'm more concerned about people
that can't see the images at all.

00:06:51.530 --> 00:06:57.080
If you have a book, like a textbook,
like this astronomy book or maybe a

00:06:57.110 --> 00:07:00.400
story like Winnie the Pooh where the
images are an illustrated children's

00:07:00.420 --> 00:07:03.200
story where the images are an
important part of the content,

00:07:03.390 --> 00:07:08.150
then a reader who can't see those images
would be missing a big portion of it.

00:07:08.360 --> 00:07:11.370
VoiceOver already does a great job of
reading the text that's on the screen,

00:07:11.420 --> 00:07:13.810
and so we need you to give us a
little bit of information about

00:07:13.810 --> 00:07:15.970
the content of those images.

00:07:17.460 --> 00:07:20.480
So the way that you would
display an image in HTML,

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:21.610
this is kind of the bare minimum.

00:07:21.740 --> 00:07:24.600
You have an image tag with a
source attribute that points to the

00:07:24.680 --> 00:07:27.700
file name of the image resource.

00:07:27.990 --> 00:07:34.000
Accessibility is important enough that
this wouldn't even be valid at EPUB.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
It wouldn't be valid HTML.

00:07:36.180 --> 00:07:39.250
Accessibility is important enough
that the alt attribute is actually

00:07:39.250 --> 00:07:40.900
a requirement for validation.

00:07:40.900 --> 00:07:45.890
So you wouldn't even be able to push this
book up to the iBook store at this point.

00:07:45.900 --> 00:07:50.270
And so some publishers know about this
constraint and they do this to fix it.

00:07:50.270 --> 00:07:52.560
They give it an empty alt attribute.

00:07:52.560 --> 00:07:55.580
And this is okay in some circumstances
if it's a purely decorative

00:07:55.580 --> 00:07:59.900
image like maybe a decorative
horizontal rule between paragraphs.

00:07:59.960 --> 00:08:00.400
That's okay.

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:05.400
But chances are most of your images in
your books are actually content images.

00:08:06.640 --> 00:08:10.020
And so sometimes we catch people
doing something like this,

00:08:10.090 --> 00:08:14.200
alt equals image,
which is not really any better.

00:08:14.200 --> 00:08:16.420
In fact, it might be a little bit worse.

00:08:16.510 --> 00:08:18.750
And the fact that it doesn't
give us any kind of information,

00:08:18.810 --> 00:08:23.120
we'll see alt equals illustration or alt
equals photograph or alt equals chart.

00:08:23.190 --> 00:08:26.080
Maybe chart's a little bit better,
but it still doesn't

00:08:26.080 --> 00:08:27.420
give us the full picture.

00:08:27.670 --> 00:08:31.750
It doesn't give us any useful information
about the content of the image.

00:08:32.390 --> 00:08:37.260
And so what you need to do is actually
provide a human-readable sentence or,

00:08:37.290 --> 00:08:41.020
you know,
short phrase that describes the content

00:08:41.020 --> 00:08:45.610
of the image in enough detail for the
user to get the point of why it's there.

00:08:45.780 --> 00:08:49.990
And that allows an accessible book
to go from something like this to

00:08:50.060 --> 00:08:54.460
something more like this where the
images are actually read out as text

00:08:54.540 --> 00:08:58.080
and that allows the reader to paint
a picture in their mind of the book

00:08:58.160 --> 00:09:02.270
author's intention which is really
what books are all about anyway.

00:09:02.930 --> 00:09:09.450
