00:35:10.700 --> 00:35:12.640
But HTML only goes so far.

00:35:12.660 --> 00:35:16.400
It was originally designed
for static documents.

00:35:16.400 --> 00:35:19.000
More recently, people have been using
it for web applications,

00:35:19.020 --> 00:35:21.100
but there's some semantics
that get lost in there,

00:35:21.100 --> 00:35:25.350
and HTML5 is fixing some of that,
but there's still some places

00:35:25.450 --> 00:35:28.890
where HTML falls short,
and that's where ARIA comes in.

00:35:29.410 --> 00:35:33.740
It's a W3C specification and
it allows web pages to declare

00:35:33.790 --> 00:35:37.130
themselves as applications and
give additional semantics about

00:35:37.220 --> 00:35:39.760
the parts of their application.

00:35:39.760 --> 00:35:43.480
Like this thing is a button and
it's disabled or this thing is

00:35:43.560 --> 00:35:48.660
a slider and its value is 64% or
